<P>
No Decision by USDA: No decision has been made on how to squeeze $2 billion out 
of farm programs to meet federal spending goals, but analysts are looking at 
all possibilities, Agriculture Secretary Clayton K. Yeutter said. "We'll find a 
way to do so, because that's a requirement of the (budget) process," Yeutter 
told reporters. About $2 billion will have to be whittled from programs in the 
fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. Those cuts were not specified in the budget 
proposals submitted by the outgoing Reagan Administration in January and were 
left open to be negotiated with Congress. Options for cutting USDA farm program 
spending include further reductions in target prices for major crops, including 
wheat, corn and cotton. Those are prices used in a formula to help determine 
federal subsidies to farmers who participate in annual crop programs. 
